Binominal Distributition using SciPy (SciPy > stats > binom)¶

In [45]:
#import scipy.stat as st
In [16]:
from scipy.stats import binom    
import numpy as np
In [3]:
# Cumulative distribution Function
# binom.cdf(K, N, P) 
# K: is the number of defectives or less, which is =2
# N is that how many number of pieces you are selecting = 20
# P: Probability is 0.12 or 12 percent
binom.cdf(2, 20, 0.12)
Out[3]:
0.5631315224061946
In [4]:
# PMF: Probability Mass Function
binom.pmf(2, 20, 0.12)
Out[4]:
0.27403383702748796
In [5]:
binom.pmf(1, 20, 0.12)
Out[5]:
0.211534891740517
In [6]:
binom.pmf(0, 20, 0.12)
Out[6]:
0.07756279363818959
In [10]:
# Mean, Variable, Standard Deviation
binom.mean(20, 0.12)
Out[10]:
2.4
In [11]:
binom.var(20, 0.12)
Out[11]:
2.112
In [12]:
binom.std(20, 0.12)
Out[12]:
1.453272169966796
In [13]:
# The probability of getting more than two defectives.So far,what you calculated here was two or less.
1-binom.cdf(2, 20, 0.12)
Out[13]:
0.4368684775938054
In [14]:
# SF: Survival Function  =   1- cdf
binom.sf(2, 20, 0.12)
Out[14]:
0.4368684775938054
In [ ]:
# binom.cdf(k,n,p) - Cumulative distribution function - for less than or equal to 2
# binom.pmf(k,n,p) - Probability mass function - for exact two defects
# binom.sf(k,n,p) - for more than 2 (similar to 1-cdf)
# binom.mean(n,p) - for mean of the distribution
# binom.var(n,p) - for variance of the distribution
# binom.std(n,p) - for standard deviation of the distribution

In [ ]:
# poisson.cdf(k,mu) - Cumulative distribution function - for less than or equal to 
# poisson.pmf(k,mu) - Probability mass function - for exact value
# poisson.sf(k,mu) - for more than (similar to 1-cdf)
# poisson.mean(mu) - for mean of the distribution
# poisson.var(mu) - for variance of the distribution
# poisson.std(mu) - for standard deviation of the distribution
In [89]:
# cdf + sf =1
# cdf = upto 7 (Cumulative)
# sf = after 7 (Cumulative)
# so, sf = 1 - cdf
poisson.sf(7,3.6)
Out[89]:
0.030789275359657444

norm.cdf(x,mu,sigma) - Cumulative distribution function - for less than or equal to norm.pdf(x,mu,sigma) - Probability density function (not Probability mass function) - for exact value norm.sf(x,mu,sigma) - for more than (similar to 1-cdf) norm.mean(mu) - for mean of the distribution norm.var(mu) - for variance of the distribution norm.std(mu) - for standard deviation of the distribution
